$frontmatter {
  title: Tools
  description: Define tools with macros, collect them into a Toolset, and execute them in user code.
  tags = ["tools", "macros"]
}

"#": Tools

"intro" = ```markdown
Tools are declared with macros but **never executed by the library**. User code owns the tool loop.
The library handles schema generation, tool call decoding, and transcript recording.
```

"toc".$toc = true

@ "define-input" {
  "##": Define a Tool Input

  "body" = ```markdown
Mark a struct with `#[tool_input]` to turn it into a tool definition. The struct must derive
`JsonSchema` and `Serialize`/`Deserialize` so the library can generate a JSON Schema for the
model and decode the model's tool call payload:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::tool_input;
use schemars::JsonSchema;
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

#[derive(Clone, Debug, Serialize, Deserialize, JsonSchema)]
struct SearchResult {
    snippets: Vec<String>,
}

#[tool_input(name = "web_search", output = SearchResult)]
#[derive(Clone, Debug, Serialize, Deserialize, JsonSchema)]
struct WebSearchArgs {
    /// The query to search for.
    query: String,
    /// Maximum number of results to return. Defaults to 5.
    max_results: Option<u32>,
}
```

  "body-2" = ```markdown
The `name` attribute sets the tool name seen by the model. The `output` attribute names the result
type that your tool implementation returns — it is used only for type safety at the call site.

Doc-comments on fields are included in the JSON Schema as field descriptions.
```

}

@ "define-fn" {
  "##": Define a Tool Function (Optional)

  "body" = ```markdown
`#[tool_fn]` wraps an `async fn` and attaches it to the tool input struct as an implementation hint.
This is optional — you can execute tools any way you like without `#[tool_fn]`:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::tool_fn;

#[tool_fn(WebSearchArgs)]
async fn web_search(args: WebSearchArgs) -> SearchResult {
    // your real implementation here
    SearchResult { snippets: vec![format!("Result for: {}", args.query)] }
}
```

}

@ "toolset" {
  "##": Collect into a Toolset

  "body" = ```markdown
`#[derive(Toolset)]` generates a typed call enum and a selector type. Group all the tools your
application exposes into one enum:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::Toolset;
use schemars::JsonSchema;
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

#[derive(Clone, Debug, Serialize, Deserialize, JsonSchema, Toolset)]
enum AppTools {
    WebSearch(WebSearchArgs),
    ReadFile(ReadFileArgs),
    WriteFile(WriteFileArgs),
}
```

  "body-2" = ```markdown
The derive generates `AppToolsCall` (the decoded call enum) and `AppToolsSelector` (a schema-bearing
selector type). Selectors retain a typed path back to `ToolDef`, so they can be passed directly into
`ToolPolicy::AllowOnly(...)`.
```

}

@ "policy" {
  "##": Tool Policy

  "body" = ```markdown
`ToolPolicy<T>` controls which tools are advertised to the model and what calling behaviour is
expected:

| Policy | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `Disabled` | No tools advertised |
| `AllowAll` | All tools in the Toolset are available |
| `AllowOnly(Vec<Selector>)` | Only the listed tools are advertised |
| `RequireAll` | All tools must be called before the turn completes |
| `RequireOnly(Vec<Selector>)` | The model must call exactly these tools |

Use `.tools::<T>()` on a turn builder to enable tools, then optionally narrow the policy:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::AppToolsSelector;

let outcome = session
    .text_turn()
    .tools::<AppTools>()
    .allow_only([AppToolsSelector::WebSearch])  // only web_search is available this turn
    .collect()
    .await?;
```

}

@ "execute" {
  "##": Executing Tool Calls

  "body" = ```markdown
Tool execution always happens in user code. When the model requests tool calls, match on the
decoded `AppToolsCall` enum:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::{TextStepOutcomeWithTools, ToolResult};

loop {
    let outcome = session
        .text_turn()
        .tools::<AppTools>()
        .collect()
        .await?;

    match outcome {
        TextStepOutcomeWithTools::NeedsTools(round) => {
            let mut results = Vec::new();

            for call in round.tool_calls.iter().cloned() {
                let result = match call {
                    AppToolsCall::WebSearch(c) => {
                        let output = web_search(c.args().clone()).await;
                        c.complete(output).unwrap()
                    }
                    AppToolsCall::ReadFile(c) => {
                        let output = read_file(c.args().clone()).await;
                        c.complete(output).unwrap()
                    }
                    AppToolsCall::WriteFile(c) => {
                        let output = write_file(c.args().clone()).await;
                        c.complete(output).unwrap()
                    }
                };
                results.push(result);
            }

            round.commit(&mut session, results)?;
        }
        TextStepOutcomeWithTools::Finished(result) => {
            println!("{}", result.assistant_text());
            session.commit_text_with_tools(result);
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

  "tip".$mark.alert = "TIP"
  "tip" = ```markdown
For single-tool rounds, `round.expect_one()?` is cleaner than iterating the call vector.
```

}

@ "nested" {
  "##": Nested Toolsets

  "body" = ```markdown
Tool inputs can themselves contain other types that derive `Toolset` if you need hierarchical tool
namespacing. See `crates/lutum/examples/nested_toolset.rs` for a worked example.
```

}
